defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.activated.des: called when the keep-alive component is activated.
defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.activated.rem: This hook is not called during server-side rendering.
After the instance is initialized, the data observer and event/watcher are called before the event configuration.
defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.beforeDestroy: Called before the instance is destroyed. At this step, the instance is still fully available.
This hook is not called during server-side rendering.
defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.beforeMount.d: Called before the start of the mount: the relevant render function is called for the first time. This hook is not called during server-side rendering.
defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.beforeRouteEn: Called before the corresponding route for rendering this component is confirmed. Do not! can! Get the component instance `this`. Because when the guard is executed, the component instance has not been created.
defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.beforeRouteLe: Called when the navigation leaves the corresponding route of the component. Can access component instance `this`
defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.beforeRouteUp:
Called when the current route changes, but the component is reused. For example, for a path /foo/:id with dynamic parameters, when jumping between /foo/1 and /foo/2, 
. Since the same Foo component will be rendered, the component instance will be reused. And this hook will be called in this case. Can access component instance `this`
Called when the data is updated, before the virtual DOM is patched. This is suitable for accessing the existing DOM before the update, such as manually removing the added event listener.
This hook is not called during server-side rendering, because only the first rendering will be performed on the server-side.
defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.comments.desc: When set to true, HTML comments in the template will be preserved and rendered. The default behavior is to discard them.
defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.comments.rema: This option is only available when compiling in the browser in the full build version.
defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.components.de: Contains a hash table of the components available for the Vue instance.
defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.computed.desc: The calculated properties will be mixed into the Vue instance. The this context of all getters and setters are automatically bound to Vue instances.
defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.computed.exam:
var vm = new Vue({
  data: { a: 1 },
  computed: {
       aDouble: function () {
      return this.a * 2
    },
      aPlus: {
      get: function () {
        return this.a + 1
      },
      set: function (v) {
        this.a = v - 1
      }
    }
  }
})
vm.aPlus   // => 2
vm.aPlus = 3
vm.a       // => 2
vm.aDouble // => 4
defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.created.descr: It is called immediately after the instance is created. In this step, the instance has completed the following configurations: data observer, calculation of attributes and methods, and watch/event event callbacks. However, the mounting phase has not yet started, and the $el property is currently not visible.
defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.data.descript: The data object of the Vue instance.
defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.data.example:
var data = { a: 1 }

var vm = new Vue({
  data: data
})
vm.a // => 1
vm.$data === data // => true

var Component = Vue.extend({
  data: function () {
	return { a: 1 }
  }
})
defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.deactivated.d: Called when the keep-alive component is disabled.
defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.deactivated.r: This hook is not called during server-side rendering.
defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.delimiters.de: Change the plain text to insert the separator.
defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.destroyed.des: Called after the Vue instance is destroyed. After the call, everything indicated by the Vue instance will be unbound, all event listeners will be removed, and all child instances will be destroyed.
defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.destroyed.rem: This hook is not called during server-side rendering.
defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.directives.de: Contains a hash table of the instructions available for the Vue instance.
defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.el.descriptio: Provide an existing DOM element on the page as the mount target of the Vue instance. It can be a CSS selector or an HTMLElement instance.
defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.errorCaptured: 2.5.0+ new is called when an error from descendant components is caught. This hook will receive three parameters: the error object, the component instance where the error occurred, and a string containing the source of the error. This hook can return false to prevent the error from continuing to propagate upward.
defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.extends.descr: Allows declaration to extend another component (can be a simple option object or constructor) without using Vue.extend. This is mainly to facilitate the expansion of single-file components.
defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.extends.examp:
var CompA = { ... }
var CompB = {
  extends: CompA,
  ...
}
defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.filters.descr: A hash table containing the filters available for the Vue instance.
defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.functional.de: Make the component stateless (no data) and no instance (no this context). They use a simple render function to return virtual nodes to make them easier to render.
By default, attribute bindings of the parent scope that are not considered props will be 'retreated' and applied as normal HTML attributes to the root element of the child component. When writing a component that wraps a target element or another component, this may not always conform to the expected behavior. By setting inheritAttrs to false, these default behaviors will be removed. These features can be made effective through the instance attribute $attrs (also new in 2.4), and can be explicitly bound to non-root elements through v-bind.
This option does not affect the binding of class and style.
defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.inject.descri: Need to be used with provide.
defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.inject.remark: provide and inject mainly provide use cases for high-level plug-in/component libraries. It is not recommended for direct use in application code.
defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.methods.descr: Methods will be mixed into the Vue instance. These methods can be accessed directly through the VM instance, or used in instruction expressions. This in the method is automatically bound to a Vue instance.
defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.methods.examp:
var vm = new Vue({
  data: { a: 1 },
  methods: {
    plus: function () {
      this.a++
    }
  }
})
vm.plus()
vm.a // 2
defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.methods.remar: Note that arrow functions should not be used to define method functions (eg plus: () => this.a++). The reason is that the arrow function is bound to the context of the parent scope, so this will not point to the Vue instance as expected, and this.a will be undefined.
defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.mixins.descri:
The mixins option accepts an array of mixed objects. These mixed instance objects can contain options like normal instance objects, and they will finally be merged using the same option merge logic in Vue.extend(). Example: If your mixin contains a hook and the creation component itself also has one, two functions will be called. 
Mixin hooks are called in sequence according to the incoming order, and are called before calling the hooks of the component itself.
defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.mixins.exampl:
var mixin = {
  created: function () { console.log(1) }
}
var vm = new Vue({
  created: function () { console.log(2) },
  mixins: [mixin]
})
// => 1
// => 2
defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.model.descrip: Allows a custom component to customize prop and event when using v-model. By default, the v-model on a component will use value as prop and input as event, but some input types such as radio buttons and checkbox buttons may want to use value prop for different purposes. Use the model option to avoid conflicts caused by these situations.
defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.model.example:
Vue.component('my-checkbox', {
  model: {
    prop: 'checked',
    event: 'change'
  },
  props: {
    // this allows using the `value` prop for a different purpose
    value: String,
    // use `checked` as the prop which take the place of `value`
    checked: {
      type: Number,
      default: 0
    }
  },
  // ...
})



上述代码相当于：
defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.mounted.descr: el is replaced by the newly created vm.$el, and the hook is called after it is mounted on the instance. If the root instance mounts an element in the document, vm.$el is also in the document when mounted is called.
defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.mounted.examp:
Note mounted does not promise that all sub-components are also mounted together. 
If you want to wait until the entire view is rendered, you can replace mounted with vm.$nextTick ：

	mounted: function () {
	  this.$nextTick(function () {
		// Code that will run only after the
		// entire view has been rendered
	  })
	}
defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.mounted.remar: This hook is not called during server-side rendering.
defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.name.descript:
Allow component templates to call themselves recursively. Note that when the component is registered globally with Vue.component(), the global ID is automatically used as the component's name. 

Another benefit of specifying the name option is to facilitate debugging. Named components have more friendly warning messages. In addition, when there is vue-devtools, unnamed components will be displayed as <AnonymousComponent>, which has no semantics. By providing the name option, a component tree with more semantic information can be obtained.
defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.parent.descri: Specify the parent instance of the created instance, and establish a parent-child relationship between the two. The child instance can use this.$parent to access the parent instance, and the child instance is pushed into the $children array of the parent instance.
defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.parent.remark: Use $parent and $children sparingly-their main purpose is to serve as an emergency method for accessing components. It is more recommended to use props and events to achieve parent-child component communication
defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.props.descrip: props can be an array or an object, used to receive data from the parent component. Props can be a simple array, or use an object as a substitute. The object allows configuration of advanced options, such as type detection, custom checksums, and setting default values.
defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.props.example:
Vue.component('props-demo-simple', {
  props: ['size', 'myMessage']
})
Vue.component('props-demo-advanced', {
  props: {    height: Number,
       age: {
      type: Number,
      default: 0,
      required: true,
      validator: function (value) {
        return value >= 0
      }
    }
  }
})
defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.propsData.des: Pass props when creating an instance. The main function is to facilitate testing.
defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.propsData.exa:
var Comp = Vue.extend({
  props: ['msg'],
  template: '
{{ msg }}
'
})

var vm = new Comp({
  propsData: {
    msg: 'hello'
  }
})
defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.provide.descr: Need to be used with inject
defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.provide.remar: provide and inject mainly provide use cases for high-level plug-in/component libraries. It is not recommended for direct use in application code.
defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.render.descri: The replacement scheme of string templates allows you to take advantage of JavaScript's maximum programming capabilities. The rendering function receives a createElement method as the first parameter to create a VNode.
defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.render.remark: If the render function in the Vue option exists, the Vue constructor will not compile the rendering function from the HTML template extracted from the template option or the mounted element specified by the el option.
defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.renderError.d: New in 2.2.0. Only work in a developer environment. When the render function encounters an error, another rendering output is provided. The error will be passed to renderError as the second parameter. This function is very useful in conjunction with hot-reload.
defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.renderError.e:
new Vue({
  render (h) {
    throw new Error('oops')
  },
  renderError (h, err) {
    return h('pre', { style: { color: 'red' }}, err.stack)
  }
}).$mount('#app')
defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.template.desc: A string template is used as the identifier of the Vue instance. The template will replace the mounted element. The content of the mounted element will be ignored, unless the content of the template has a distribution slot.
defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.template.rema: If a rendering function is included in the Vue options, the template will be ignored.
defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.updated.descr: The virtual DOM is re-rendered and patched due to data changes, after which the hook will be called.
defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.updated.remar: This hook is not called during server-side rendering.
defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.watch.descrip: For an object, the key is the expression to be observed, and the value is the corresponding callback function. The value can also be a method name, or an object containing options. The Vue instance will call $watch() when it is instantiated, traversing every attribute of the watch object.
defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.watch.example:
var vm = new Vue({
  data: {
    a: 1,
    b: 2,
    c: 3,
    d: 4,
    e: {
      f: {
        g: 5
      }
    }
  },
  watch: {
    a: function (val, oldVal) {
      console.log('new: %s, old: %s', val, oldVal)
    },
       b: 'someMethod',
        c: {
      handler: function (val, oldVal) { /* ... */ },
      deep: true
    },
       d: {
      handler: function (val, oldVal) { /* ... */ },
      immediate: true
    },
    e: [
      function handle1 (val, oldVal) { /* ... */ },
      function handle2 (val, oldVal) { /* ... */ }
    ],
    // watch vm.e.f's value: {g: 5}
    'e.f': function (val, oldVal) { /* ... */ }
  }
})
vm.a = 2 // => new: 2, old: 1
defs/js/vue.2.x.ComponentOptions_.property.watch.remarks: Note that arrow functions should not be used to define watcher functions (eg searchQuery: newValue => this.updateAutocomplete(newValue)). The reason is that the arrow function is bound to the context of the parent scope, so this will not point to the Vue instance as expected, and this.updateAutocomplete will be undefined.
defs/js/vue.2.x.Vue.config_.property.devtools.descriptio: Configure whether to allow vue-devtools to check the code. The development version defaults to true, and the production version defaults to false. The production version is set to true to enable checking.
defs/js/vue.2.x.Vue.config_.property.errorHandler.descri: Specifies the processing function for uncaught errors during rendering and observation of the component. When this handler is called, you can get error information and Vue instances.
defs/js/vue.2.x.Vue.config_.property.errorHandler.exampl:
Vue.config.errorHandler = function (err, vm, info) {
  // handle error
    }
defs/js/vue.2.x.Vue.config_.property.errorHandler.remark:
Starting from 2.2.0, this hook will also catch errors in component lifecycle hooks. Similarly, when this hook is undefined, the caught error will be output through console.error to avoid app crash.


Starting from 2.4.0, this hook will also catch errors in Vue custom event handlers.
defs/js/vue.2.x.Vue.config_.property.ignoredElements.des: You must make Vue ignore custom elements outside of Vue (e.g. Web Components APIs are used). Otherwise, it will assume that you forgot to register the global component or misspelled the component name, thus throwing a warning about Unknown custom element.
defs/js/vue.2.x.Vue.config_.property.keyCodes.descriptio: Customize the key alias for v-on.
defs/js/vue.2.x.Vue.config_.property.keyCodes.example:
Vue.config.keyCodes = {
  v: 86,
  f1: 112,
    mediaPlayPause: 179,
    "media-play-pause": 179,
  up: [38, 87]
}

<input type="text" @keyup.media-play-pause="method">
defs/js/vue.2.x.Vue.config_.property.optionMergeStrategi: Options for customizing the merge strategy. The merge strategy option receives the value of the option defined on the parent instance and the child instance as the first and second parameters, and the Vue instance context is passed in as the third parameter.

Vue.config.optionMergeStrategies._my_option = function (parent, child, vm) {
	  return child + 1
	}

	const Profile = Vue.extend({
	  _my_option: 1
	})

	// Profile.options._my_option = 2
defs/js/vue.2.x.Vue.config_.property.performance.descrip: New in 2.2.0. Set to true to enable performance tracking of component initialization, compilation, rendering, and patching in the performance/timeline panel of the browser development tool. Only applicable to development mode and browsers that support performance.mark API.
defs/js/vue.2.x.Vue.config_.property.productionTip.descr: New in 2.2.0. Set to false to prevent vue from generating production prompts at startup.
defs/js/vue.2.x.Vue.config_.property.warnHandler.descrip: New in 2.4.0. Assign a custom processing function to Vue's runtime warning. Note that this will only take effect in the developer environment, it will be ignored in the production environment.
defs/js/vue.2.x.Class<Vue>_.method.$delete.description: This is an alias for the global Vue.delete. r
defs/js/vue.2.x.Class<Vue>_.method.$destroy.description: Destroy an instance completely. Clean up its connection with other instances, unbind all its instructions and event listeners.
defs/js/vue.2.x.Class<Vue>_.method.$destroy.remarks: You should not call this method in most scenarios. It is best to use v-if and v-for instructions to control the life cycle of sub-components in a data-driven manner.
defs/js/vue.2.x.Class<Vue>_.method.$emit.description: Trigger an event on the current instance. Additional parameters will be passed to the listener callback.
defs/js/vue.2.x.Class<Vue>_.method.$forceUpdate.descript: Force the Vue instance to re-render. Note that it only affects the instance itself and the subcomponents inserted into the slot content, not all subcomponents.
defs/js/vue.2.x.Class<Vue>_.method.$mount.description: If the Vue instance does not receive the el option when it is instantiated, it is in the 'unmounted' state and has no associated DOM elements. You can use vm.$mount() to manually mount an unmounted instance.
defs/js/vue.2.x.Class<Vue>_.method.$mount.example:
var MyComponent = Vue.extend({
  template: '
Hello!
'
})

new MyComponent().$mount('#app')

new MyComponent({ el: '#app' })

var component = new MyComponent().$mount()
document.getElementById('app').appendChild(component.$el)
defs/js/vue.2.x.Class<Vue>_.method.$nextTick.description: Delay the callback until after the next DOM update cycle. Use it immediately after modifying the data, and then wait for the DOM to update. It is the same as the global method Vue.nextTick, except that the callback's this is automatically bound to the instance that calls it.
defs/js/vue.2.x.Class<Vue>_.method.$nextTick.example:
new Vue({
  // ...
  methods: {
    // ...
    example: function () {
            this.message = 'changed'
            this.$nextTick(function () {
                     this.doSomethingElse()
      })
    }
  }
})
defs/js/vue.2.x.Class<Vue>_.method.$nextTick.remarks: New since 2.1.0: If no callback is provided and in an environment that supports Promise, a Promise will be returned. Please note that Vue does not come with Promise polyfills, so if your target browser does not natively support Promises (IE: you all see what I do), you have to polyfill it yourself.
defs/js/vue.2.x.Class<Vue>_.method.$off.description:
Remove custom event listener. 

	* If no parameters are provided, all event listeners will be removed; 
	* If only an event is provided, all listeners for the event will be removed;
 
	* If both an event and a callback are provided, only the listener for this callback will be removed.
defs/js/vue.2.x.Class<Vue>_.method.$on.description: Listen for custom events on the current instance. The event can be triggered by vm.$emit. The callback function will receive all the extra parameters of the incoming event trigger function.
defs/js/vue.2.x.Class<Vue>_.method.$once.description: Listen to a custom event, but only trigger it once, and remove the listener after the first trigger.
defs/js/vue.2.x.Class<Vue>_.method.$set.description: This is an alias for the global Vue.set.
defs/js/vue.2.x.Class<Vue>_.method.$watch.description: An expression or calculation property function to observe the changes of a Vue instance. The parameters obtained by the callback function are the new value and the old value. The expression only accepts supervised key paths. For more complex expressions, use a function instead.
defs/js/vue.2.x.Class<Vue>_.method.$watch.example:
vm.$watch('a.b.c', function (newVal, oldVal) {
  )

vm.$watch(
  function () {
    return this.a + this.b
  },
  function (newVal, oldVal) {
    }
)
defs/js/vue.2.x.Class<Vue>_.method.$watch.remarks: Note: When mutating (not replacing) an object or array, the old value will be the same as the new value because their references point to the same object/array. Vue will not keep a copy of the value before the mutation.
defs/js/vue.2.x.Class<Vue>_.method.compile.description: Compile the template string in the render function. Only works when built independently.
defs/js/vue.2.x.Class<Vue>_.method.compile.example:
var res = Vue.compile('
{{ msg }}
')

new Vue({
  data: {
    msg: 'hello'
  },
  render: res.render,
  staticRenderFns: res.staticRenderFns
})
defs/js/vue.2.x.Class<Vue>_.method.component.description: Register or get global components. Registration will also automatically set the name of the component with the given id.
defs/js/vue.2.x.Class<Vue>_.method.component.example:
Vue.component('my-component', Vue.extend({ /* ... */ }))

Vue.component('my-component', { /* ... */ })

var MyComponent = Vue.component('my-component')
defs/js/vue.2.x.Class<Vue>_.method.delete.description: Delete the attributes of the object. If the object is responsive, make sure to delete it to trigger an update of the view. This method is mainly used to avoid the restriction that Vue cannot detect that the property is deleted, but you should rarely use it.
defs/js/vue.2.x.Class<Vue>_.method.delete.remarks: Note that the object cannot be a Vue instance, or the root data object of a Vue instance.
defs/js/vue.2.x.Class<Vue>_.method.directive.example:
Vue.directive('my-directive', {
  bind: function () {},
  inserted: function () {},
  update: function () {},

})

Vue.directive('my-directive', function () {
var myDirective = Vue.directive('my-directive')
defs/js/vue.2.x.Class<Vue>_.method.extend.description:
Using the basic Vue constructor, create a 'subclass'. The parameter is an object that contains component options. 
						The data option is a special case, you need to pay attention-it must be a function in Vue.extend()
defs/js/vue.2.x.Class<Vue>_.method.extend.example:
<div id="mount-point"></div>

var Profile = Vue.extend({
  template: '<p>{{firstName}} {{lastName}} aka {{alias}}</p>',
  data: function () {
    return {
      firstName: 'Walter',
      lastName: 'White',
      alias: 'Heisenberg'
    }
  }
})
new Profile().$mount('#mount-point')


<p>Walter White aka Heisenberg</p>
defs/js/vue.2.x.Class<Vue>_.method.filter.description: Register or get a global filter.
defs/js/vue.2.x.Class<Vue>_.method.mixin.description: Registering a mixin globally affects every Vue instance created after registration. Plug-in authors can use mixins to inject custom behaviors into components. Not recommended for use in application code.
defs/js/vue.2.x.Class<Vue>_.method.nextTick.description: The delayed callback is executed after the next DOM update cycle ends. Use this method immediately after modifying the data to get the updated DOM.
defs/js/vue.2.x.Class<Vue>_.method.nextTick.remarks: New since 2.1.0: If no callback is provided and in an environment that supports Promise, a Promise will be returned. Please note that Vue does not come with a Promise polyfill, so if your target browser does not natively support Promise (IE: What do you guys see me for), you have to provide your own polyfill.
defs/js/vue.2.x.Class<Vue>_.method.set.description: Add a property to the responsive object, and make sure that this new property is also responsive and trigger a view update. It must be used to add new properties to responsive objects, because Vue cannot detect ordinary new properties (such as this.myObject.newProperty ='hi')
defs/js/vue.2.x.Class<Vue>_.method.set.remarks: Note that the object cannot be a Vue instance, or the root data object of a Vue instance.
defs/js/vue.2.x.Class<Vue>_.method.use.description:
Install the Vue.js plugin. If the plug-in is an object, the install method must be provided. If the plugin is a function, it will be used as the install method. When the install method is called, Vue will be passed in as a parameter. 

When the install method is called multiple times by the same plugin, the plugin will only be installed once.
defs/js/vue.2.x.Class<Vue>_.property.$attrs.description: Contains feature bindings (except class and style) that are not recognized (and obtained) as props in the parent scope. When a component does not declare any prop, it will include all parent scope bindings (except class and style), and can pass in internal components through v-bind="$attrs"-in the creation of high-level It is very useful when it comes to components.
defs/js/vue.2.x.Class<Vue>_.property.$children.descripti: The immediate child component of the current instance. It should be noted that $children does not guarantee the order, nor is it reactive. If you find yourself trying to use $children for data binding, consider using an array with v-for to generate child components, and use Array as the real source.
defs/js/vue.2.x.Class<Vue>_.property.$data.description: The data object observed by the Vue instance. The Vue instance delegates access to the properties of its data object.
defs/js/vue.2.x.Class<Vue>_.property.$el.description: The root DOM element used by the Vue instance.
defs/js/vue.2.x.Class<Vue>_.property.$isServer.descripti: Whether the current Vue instance is running on the server.
defs/js/vue.2.x.Class<Vue>_.property.$listeners.descript: Contains the v-on event listener in the parent scope (without the .native decorator). It can pass in internal components via v-on="$listeners"-very useful when creating higher-level components.
defs/js/vue.2.x.Class<Vue>_.property.$options.descriptio: Initialization options for the current Vue instance.
defs/js/vue.2.x.Class<Vue>_.property.$options.example:
new Vue({
  customOption: 'foo',
  created: function () {
    console.log(this.$options.customOption) // => 'foo'
  }
})
defs/js/vue.2.x.Class<Vue>_.property.$parent.description: The parent instance, if the current instance has one.
defs/js/vue.2.x.Class<Vue>_.property.$props.description: The props object received by the current component. The Vue instance delegates access to the properties of its props object.
defs/js/vue.2.x.Class<Vue>_.property.$refs.description: An object that holds all DOM elements and component instances that have registered ref characteristics.
defs/js/vue.2.x.Class<Vue>_.property.$root.description: The root Vue instance of the current component tree. If the current instance does not have a parent instance, this instance will be itself.
defs/js/vue.2.x.Class<Vue>_.property.$scopedSlots.descri: Used to access scoped slots. For each slot including the default slot, this object contains a function that returns the corresponding VNode.
defs/js/vue.2.x.Class<Vue>_.property.$slots.description: Used to access the content distributed by the slot. Each named slot has its corresponding attribute (for example: the content in slot="foo" will be found in vm.$slots.foo). The default attribute includes all nodes that are not included in the named slot.
defs/js/vue.2.x.Class<Vue>_.property.$slots.example:
<blog-post>
  <h1 slot="header">
    About Me
  </h1>

  <p>Here's some page content, which will be included in vm.$slots.default, because it's not inside a named slot.</p>

  <p slot="footer">
    Copyright 2016 Evan You
  </p>

  <p>If I have some content down here, it will also be included in vm.$slots.default.</p>.
</blog-post>

Vue.component('blog-post', {
  render: function (createElement) {
    var header = this.$slots.header
    var body   = this.$slots.default
    var footer = this.$slots.footer
    return createElement('div', [
      createElement('header', header),
      createElement('main', body),
      createElement('footer', footer)
    ])
  }
})
defs/js/vue.2.x.Class<Vue>_.property.config.description: Vue.config is an object that contains Vue's global configuration.
defs/js/vue.2.x.Class<Vue>_.property.version.description: Provide the Vue installation version number in the form of a string. This is very useful for community plug-ins and components. You can adopt different strategies according to different version numbers.

defs/js/vue.3.x.ComponentOptions_.method.setup.descripti: A component option, executed before the component is created, once the props are parsed and used as the entry point of the combined API
defs/js/vue.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.activated.des: Called when the keep-alive cached component is activated.
defs/js/vue.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.activated.rem: This hook is not called during server-side rendering.
After the instance is initialized, the data observer and event/watcher are called before the event configuration.
defs/js/vue.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.beforeMount.d: Called before the start of the mount: the relevant render function is called for the first time. This hook is not called during server-side rendering.
defs/js/vue.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.beforeUnmount: Called before uninstalling the component instance. At this stage, the instance is still completely normal.
This hook is not called during server-side rendering.
Called when the data is updated, before the virtual DOM is patched. This is suitable for accessing the existing DOM before the update, such as manually removing the added event listener.
This hook is not called during server-side rendering, because only the first rendering will be performed on the server-side.
defs/js/vue.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.components.de: Contains a hash table of available components for the component instance.
defs/js/vue.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.computed.desc: The calculated properties will be mixed into the Vue instance. The this context of all getters and setters are automatically bound to Vue instances.
defs/js/vue.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.computed.exam:
const app = Vue.createApp({
  data() {
    return { a: 1 }
  },
  computed: {
       aDouble() {
      return this.a * 2
    },
       aPlus: {
      get() {
        return this.a + 1
      },
      set(v) {
        this.a = v - 1
      }
    }
  }
})

const vm = app.mount('#app')
console.log(vm.aPlus) // => 2
vm.aPlus = 3
console.log(vm.a) // => 2
console.log(vm.aDouble) // => 4
defs/js/vue.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.created.descr: It is called immediately after the instance is created. In this step, the instance has completed the following configurations: data observer, calculation of properties and methods, and watch/event event callbacks. However, the mount phase has not yet started, and $el property is not yet available.
defs/js/vue.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.data.descript: A function that returns the data object of a component instance.
defs/js/vue.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.data.example:
const data = { a: 1 }

const vm = Vue.createApp({
  data() {
    return data
  }
}).mount('#app')

console.log(vm.a) // => 1
defs/js/vue.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.deactivated.d: Called when the keep-alive cached component is disabled.
defs/js/vue.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.deactivated.r: This hook is not called during server-side rendering.
defs/js/vue.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.delimiters.de: Change the plain text to insert the separator.
defs/js/vue.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.delimiters.ex:
Vue.createApp({
  // Delimiters changed to ES6 template string style
  delimiters: ['${', '}']
})
defs/js/vue.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.directives.de: Contains a hash table of available instructions for the component instance.
defs/js/vue.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.emits.descrip: Emits can be an array or an object to trigger custom events from the component. Emits can be a simple array or an object as an alternative, allowing configuration and event verification.
defs/js/vue.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.emits.example:
const app = Vue.createApp({})

app.component('todo-item', {
  emits: ['check'],
  created() {
    this.$emit('check')
  }
})

app.component('reply-form', {
  emits: {
       click: null,

     submit: payload => {
      if (payload.email && payload.password) {
        return true
      } else {
        console.warn(`Invalid submit event payload!`)
        return false
      }
    }
  }
})
defs/js/vue.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.emits.remarks: The events listed in the emits option will not be inherited from the root element of the component and will also be removed from the $attrs property.
defs/js/vue.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.errorCaptured: Called when an error from a descendant component is caught. This hook will receive three parameters: the error object, the component instance where the error occurred, and a string containing the source of the error. This hook can return false to prevent the error from continuing to propagate upward.
This hook is not called during server-side rendering.
defs/js/vue.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.extends.descr: Allows declaration to extend another component (can be a simple option object or constructor). This is mainly to facilitate the expansion of single-file components.
defs/js/vue.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.extends.examp:
const CompA = { ... }

const CompB = {
  extends: CompA,
  ...
}
By default, attribute bindings in the parent scope that are not considered props will be 'retreated' and applied to the root element of the child component as a normal HTML attribute. When writing a component that wraps a target element or another component, this may not always conform to the expected behavior. By setting inheritAttrs to false, these default behaviors will be removed. And through the instance property $attrs can make these attributes take effect, and can be explicitly bound to non-root elements through v-bind.

app.component('base-input', {
								inheritAttrs: false,
								props: ['label', 'value'],
								emits: ['input'],
								template: `
									
								`
								})
defs/js/vue.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.inject.descri: Need to be used together with provide. The provide option should be an object or a function that returns an object. This object contains properties that can be injected into its descendants. You can use ES2015 Symbols as the key in this object, but it only works in an environment that natively supports Symbol and Reflect.ownKeys.
defs/js/vue.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.inject.remark: provide and inject mainly provide use cases for high-level plug-in/component libraries. It is not recommended for direct use in application code.
defs/js/vue.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.methods.descr: Methods will be mixed into the Vue instance. These methods can be accessed directly through the VM instance, or used in instruction expressions. This in the method is automatically bound to a Vue instance.
defs/js/vue.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.methods.examp:
const app = Vue.createApp({
  data() {
    return { a: 1 }
  },
  methods: {
    plus() {
      this.a++
    }
  }
})

const vm = app.mount('#app')

vm.plus()
console.log(vm.a) // => 2
defs/js/vue.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.methods.remar: Note that arrow functions should not be used to define method functions (eg plus: () => this.a++). The reason is that the arrow function is bound to the context of the parent scope, so this will not point to the Vue instance as expected, and this.a will be undefined.
defs/js/vue.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.mixins.descri: The mixins option accepts an array of mixed objects. These mixed instance objects can contain options like normal instance objects, and they will finally be merged using the same option merge logic in Vue.extend(). Example: If your mixin contains a hook and the creation component itself also has one, two functions will be called. Mixin hooks are called in sequence according to the incoming order, and are called before calling the component's own hook.
defs/js/vue.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.mixins.exampl:
const mixin = {
  created: function() {
    console.log(1)
  }
}

Vue.createApp({
  created() {
    console.log(2)
  },
  mixins: [mixin]
})

// => 1
// => 2
defs/js/vue.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.mounted.descr: Called after the instance is mounted, at this time Vue.createApp({}).mount() is replaced by the newly created vm.$el. If the root instance is mounted on an element in a document, vm.$el is also in the document when mounted is called.
defs/js/vue.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.mounted.remar:
This hook is not called during server-side rendering. 
							Note that mounted does not promise that all subcomponents are also mounted together.
defs/js/vue.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.name.descript: Allow component templates to call themselves recursively. Note that when the component is registered globally with Vue.createApp({}).component({}), the global ID is automatically used as the component's name.
defs/js/vue.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.props.descrip: props can be an array or an object, used to receive data from the parent component. Props can be a simple array, or use an object as a substitute. The object allows configuration of advanced options, such as type detection, custom checksums, and setting default values.
defs/js/vue.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.props.example:
const app = Vue.createApp({})

app.component('props-demo-simple', {
  props: ['size', 'myMessage']
})

app.component('props-demo-advanced', {
  props: {
       height: Number,
        age: {
    type: Number,
      default: 0,
      required: true,
      validator: value => {
        return value >= 0
      }
    }
  }
})
defs/js/vue.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.provide.descr: Need to be used with inject
defs/js/vue.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.provide.remar: provide and inject mainly provide use cases for high-level plug-in/component libraries. It is not recommended for direct use in application code.
defs/js/vue.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.render.descri: Another option for string templates allows you to take full advantage of the programming capabilities of JavaScript.
defs/js/vue.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.render.remark: The priority of the render function is higher than that of the HTML template compilation rendering function extracted from the template option of the mounted element or the built-in DOM.
defs/js/vue.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.renderTracked: Called when the tracking virtual DOM is re-rendered. The hook receives debugger event as a parameter. This event tells you which operation is tracking the component and the target object and key of the operation.
defs/js/vue.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.renderTrigger: When the virtual DOM is re-rendered as triggered.Similarly as renderTracked, it receives debugger event as a parameter. This event tells you what operation triggered the re-rendering, as well as the target object and key of the operation.
defs/js/vue.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.template.desc: A string template is used as the identifier of the Vue instance. The template will replace the mounted elements. The content of the mounted element will be ignored, unless the content of the template has a distribution slot.
defs/js/vue.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.template.rema: If a rendering function is included in the Vue options, the template will be ignored.
defs/js/vue.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.unmounted.des: Called after the component instance is uninstalled. When this hook is called, all instructions of the component instance are unbound, all event listeners are removed, and all child component instances are unloaded.
defs/js/vue.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.unmounted.rem: This hook is not called during server-side rendering.
defs/js/vue.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.updated.descr: The virtual DOM is re-rendered and patched due to data changes, after which the hook will be called.
defs/js/vue.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.updated.remar: This hook is not called during server-side rendering.
defs/js/vue.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.watch.descrip: For an object, the key is the expression to be observed, and the value is the corresponding callback function. The value can also be a method name, or an object containing options. The Vue instance will call $watch() when it is instantiated, traversing every attribute of the watch object.
defs/js/vue.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.watch.example:
const app = Vue.createApp({
data() {
  return {
    a: 1,
    b: 2,
    c: {
      d: 4
    },
    e: 'test',
    f: 5
  }
},
watch: {
  a(val, oldVal) {
    console.log(`new: ${val}, old: ${oldVal}`)
  },
    b: 'someMethod',
   c: {
    handler(val, oldVal) {
      console.log('c changed')
    },
    deep: true
  },
   e: {
    handler(val, oldVal) {
      console.log('e changed')
    },
    immediate: true
  },
    f: [
    'handle1',
    function handle2(val, oldVal) {
      console.log('handle2 triggered')
    },
    {
      handler: function handle3(val, oldVal) {
      console.log('handle3 triggered')
    }
    /* ... */
    }
  ]
},
methods: {
  someMethod() {
    console.log('b changed')
  },
  handle1() {
    console.log('handle 1 triggered')
  }
}
})

const vm = app.mount('#app')

vm.a = 3 // => new: 3, old: 1
defs/js/vue.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.watch.remarks: Note that arrow functions should not be used to define watcher functions  (Example: searchQuery: newValue => this.updateAutocomplete(newValue))。The reason is that the arrow function is bound to the context of the parent scope, so this will not point to the Vue instance as expected, and this.updateAutocomplete will be undefined.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Config_.property.errorHandler.descriptio: Specify a handler to handle uncaught errors thrown by the listener during the execution of the component rendering method. When this processing function is called, error information and application examples can be obtained.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Config_.property.globalProperties.descri: Add a global property that can be accessed in any component instance within the application. When the property name conflicts, the property of the component will take precedence.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Config_.property.isCustomElement.descrip: Specify a method to identify custom elements defined outside of Vue (for example, using Web Components API). If the component meets this condition, there is no need to register locally or globally, and Vue will not throw a warning about Unknown custom element.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Config_.property.optionMergeStrategies.d:
Define merge strategies for custom options. 
						The merge strategy option receives the value of the option defined on the parent instance and the child instance as the first and second parameters, and the reference context instance is passed in as the third parameter.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Config_.property.optionMergeStrategies.e:
const app = Vue.createApp({
  mounted() {
    console.log(this.$options.hello)
  }
})

app.config.optionMergeStrategies.hello = (parent, child, vm) => {
  return `Hello, ${child}`
}

app.mixin({
  hello: 'Vue'
})

// 'Hello, Vue
defs/js/vue.3.x.Config_.property.performance.description: Set to true to enable performance tracking of component initialization, compilation, rendering, and update in the performance/timeline panel of the browser development tool. Only applicable to development mode and browsers that support performance.mark API.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Config_.property.warnHandler.description: Specify a custom processing function for Vue's runtime warnings. Note that this will only take effect in a development environment, it will be ignored in a production environment.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Config_.property.warnHandler.example:

defs/js/vue.3.x.LifeCycleFunction_.property.onMounted.re:

defs/js/vue.3.x.LifeCycleFunction_.property.onRenderTrig: When the virtual DOM is re-rendered as triggered.Similarly as renderTracked, it receives debugger event as a parameter. This event tells you what operation triggered the re-rendering, as well as the target object and key of the operation.
