defs/js/vue.3.x.Vue_.method.activated.description: Called when the keep-alive cached component is activated.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.activated.description: Called when the keep-alive cached component is activated.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Vue_.method.deactivated.description: Called when the keep-alive component is disabled.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.deactivated.descripti: Called when the keep-alive component is disabled.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.render.description: The replacement scheme of string templates allows you to take advantage of JavaScript's maximum programming capabilities. The rendering function receives a createElement method as the first parameter to create a VNode.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.$emit.description: Trigger an event on the current instance. Additional parameters will be passed to the listener callback.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.$forceUpdate.descript: Force the Vue instance to re-render. Note that it only affects the instance itself and the subcomponents inserted into the slot content, not all subcomponents.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.$nextTick.description: Delay the callback until after the next DOM update cycle. Use it immediately after modifying the data, and then wait for the DOM to update. It is the same as the global method nextTick, except that the callback this is automatically bound to the instance that calls it.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.$nextTick.example:
Vue.createApp({
  // ...
  methods: {
  // ...
  example() {
    // modify data
    this.message = 'changed'
    // DOM is not updated yet
    this.$nextTick(function() {
      // DOM is now updated
      // `this` is bound to the current instance
      this.doSomethingElse()
    })
   }
  }
})
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.$watch.description: Listen for changes in the result of the responsive property or function calculation on the component instance. The parameters obtained by the callback function are the new value and the old value. We can only pass the top-level data, prop, or computed property name as a string. For more complex expressions, use a function instead.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.$watch.example:
const app = Vue.createApp({
	data() {
		return {
			a: 1,
			b: 2,
			c: {
				d: 3,
				e: 4
			}
		}
	},
	created() {
				this.$watch('a', (newVal, oldVal) => {
			})

		this.$watch(
		() => this.c.d,
		(newVal, oldVal) => {
					}
	)

		this.$watch(
								() => this.a + this.b,
			(newVal, oldVal) => {
							}
		)
	}
})
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.component.description: Register or retrieve global components. Registration also automatically sets the name of the component using the given name parameter.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.computed.description: Use the getter function and return an unchanging, reactive ref object for the value returned from the getter.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.computed.example:
const shallow = shallowRef({
	greet: 'Hello, world'
})

 "Hello, world"
watchEffect(() => {
	console.log(shallow.value.greet)
})

shallow.value.greet = 'Hello, universe'

 "Hello, universe"
triggerRef(shallow)
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.createApp.description: Returns an application instance that provides the application context. The entire component tree mounted by the application instance shares the same context.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.createRenderer.descri:
The createRenderer function accepts two generic parameters: HostNode and HostElement, corresponding to the Node and Element types in the host environment. 
					For example, for runtime-dom, HostNode will be the DOM Node interface, and HostElement will be the DOM Element interface.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.createRenderer.exampl:
import { createRenderer } from 'vue'
const { render, createApp } = createRenderer({
  patchProp,
  ...nodeOps
})
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.customRef.description: Create a custom ref and explicitly control its dependency tracking and update triggers. It needs a factory function, which receives track and trigger functions as parameters, and should return an object with get and set.
Create an asynchronous component that will only be loaded when needed.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.defineComponent.descr: From an implementation point of view, defineComponent only returns the object passed to it. However, as far as the type is concerned, the returned value has a synthetic type constructor for manual rendering functions, TSX and IDE tool support.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.defineProps.descripti: To declare props and emits options and have complete type inference, you can use the defineprops and defineemits APIs, both of which are automatically available in < script setup >.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.h.description: Return a 'virtual node', usually abbreviated as VNode: an ordinary object that contains information describing to Vue what kind of node it should render on the page, including descriptions of all child nodes. Its purpose is to be used for manually written rendering functions
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.inject.description:
Set a value that can be injected into all components in the application range. The component should use inject to receive the provided value.
						From the perspective of provide/inject, you can think of an application as an ancestor at the root level, and the root component is its only child.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.isProxy.description: Check whether the object is a reactive or readonly created proxy.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.isReactive.descriptio: Check if the object is a reactive proxy created by reactive.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.isReadonly.descriptio: Check whether the object is a read-only proxy created by readonly.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.isRef.description: Check whether the object is a ref object.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.markRaw.description: Mark an object so that it will never be converted to a proxy. Return the object itself.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.mixin.description: Mixing is applied across the entire range of applications. Once registered, they can use it in any component template in the current application. Plug-in authors can use this method to inject custom behaviors into components. It is not recommended to use in application code.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.mount.description: Mount the root component of the application instance on the provided DOM element.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.nextTick.description: Postpone the callback until after the next DOM update cycle. Use it immediately after changing some data to wait for the DOM to update.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.nextTick.example:
import { createApp, nextTick } from 'vue'

const app = createApp({
  setup() {
    const message = ref('Hello!')
    const changeMessage = async newMessage => {
      message.value = newMessage
      await nextTick()
      console.log('Now DOM is updated')
    }
  }
})
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.onActivated.descripti: Called when the keep-alive cached component is activated.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.onActivated.remarks: Called when the keep-alive cached component is activated.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.onBeforeMount.descrip: Called before the start of the mount: the relevant render function is called for the first time. This hook is not called during server-side rendering.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.onBeforeUnmount.descr: Called before uninstalling the component instance. At this stage, the instance is still completely normal.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.onBeforeUnmount.remar: This hook is not called during server-side rendering.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.onBeforeUpdate.descri: Called when the data is updated, before the virtual DOM is patched. This is suitable for accessing the existing DOM before the update, such as manually removing the added event listener.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.onBeforeUpdate.remark: This hook is not called during server-side rendering, because only the first rendering will be performed on the server-side.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.onErrorCaptured.descr: Called when an error from a descendant component is caught. This hook will receive three parameters: the error object, the component instance where the error occurred, and a string containing the source of the error. This hook can return false to prevent the error from continuing to propagate upward.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.onErrorCaptured.remar: This hook is not called during server-side rendering.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.onMounted.description: Called after the instance is mounted, at this time Vue.createApp({}).mount() is replaced by the newly created vm.$el. If the root instance is mounted on an element in a document, vm.$el is also in the document when mounted is called.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.onMounted.remarks:
This hook is not called during server-side rendering. 
						Note that mounted does not promise that all subcomponents are also mounted together.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.onRenderTracked.descr: Called when the tracking virtual DOM is re-rendered. The hook receives debugger event as a parameter. This event tells you which operation is tracking the component and the target object and key of the operation.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.onRenderTriggered.des: When the virtual DOM is re-rendered as triggered.Similarly as renderTracked, it receives debugger event as a parameter. This event tells you what operation triggered the re-rendering, as well as the target object and key of the operation.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.onUnmounted.descripti: Called after the component instance is uninstalled. When this hook is called, all instructions of the component instance are unbound, all event listeners are removed, and all child component instances are unloaded.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.onUnmounted.remarks: This hook is not called during server-side rendering.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.onUpdated.description: The virtual DOM is re-rendered and patched due to data changes, after which the hook will be called.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.onUpdated.remarks: This hook is not called during server-side rendering.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.provide.description:
Set a value that can be injected into all components in the application range. The component should use inject to receive the provided value.
						From the perspective of provide/inject, you can think of an application as an ancestor at the root level, and the root component is its only child.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.reactive.description: Return a responsive copy of the object
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.readonly.description: Get an object (responsive or pure object) or ref and return the read-only proxy of the original proxy. Read-only proxies are deep: any nested property accessed is also read-only.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.readonly.example:
const original = reactive({ count: 0 })

const copy = readonly(original)

watchEffect(() => {
		console.log(copy.count)
})

original.count++

copy.count++
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.ref.description: Accepts an internal value and returns a responsive and mutable ref object. The ref object has a single property .value that points to an internal value.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.resolveComponent.desc:
resolveComponent can only be used in render or setup functions.
					If available in the current application instance, the component is allowed to be resolved by name.
					Return a Component. If it is not found, it returns undefined.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.resolveComponent.exam:
import { resolveComponent } from 'vue'
render() {
  const MyComponent = resolveComponent('MyComponent')
}
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.resolveDirective.desc:
resolveComponent can only be used in render or setup functions.
					If it is available in the current application instance, a directive is allowed to be resolved by its name. 
					Return a Directive. If it is not found, it returns undefined.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.resolveDirective.exam:
const app = Vue.createApp({})
app.directive('highlight', {})

import { resolveDirective } from 'vue'
render () {
  const highlightDirective = resolveDirective('highlight')
}
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.resolveDynamicCompone:
resolveDynamicComponent can only be used in render or setup functions.
					It is allowed to use the same mechanism as <component :is=""> to resolve a component.
					Returns the resolved Component or newly created VNode, where the component name is used as the node label. If the Component cannot be found, a warning will be issued.

import { resolveDynamicComponent } from 'vue'
render () {
  const MyComponent = resolveDynamicComponent('MyComponent')
}
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.setup.description: A component option, executed before the component is created, once the props are parsed and used as the entry point of the combined API
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.shallowReactive.descr: Create a responsive proxy that tracks the responsiveness of its own property, but does not perform deep responsive conversion of nested objects (exposing the original value).
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.shallowReadonly.descr: Create a proxy to make its own property read-only, but does not perform deep read-only conversion of nested objects (exposing the original value).
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.shallowRef.descriptio: Create a ref that tracks its own .value changes, but does not make its value responsive.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.shallowRef.example:
const foo = shallowRef({})
foo.value = {}
isReactive(foo.value) // false
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.toRaw.description: Return the original object of the reactive or readonly proxy.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.toRef.description: Can be used to create a ref for the property of the source responsive object. The ref can then be passed out to maintain a responsive connection to its source property.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.toRefs.description: Convert the responsive object into a normal object, where each property of the result object is a ref that points to the corresponding property of the original object.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.triggerRef.descriptio: Manually execute any effects associated with shallowRef](#shallowref).
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.triggerRef.example:
const shallow = shallowRef({
	greet: 'Hello, world'
})

 "Hello, world"
watchEffect(() => {
	console.log(shallow.value.greet)
})

// 这不会触发作用，因为 ref 很浅层
shallow.value.greet = 'Hello, universe'

// 记录 "Hello, universe"
triggerRef(shallow)
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.unmount.description: Uninstall the root component of the application instance on the provided DOM element.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.unref.description: If the parameter is ref, the internal value is returned, otherwise the parameter itself is returned. val = isRef(val) ? val.value : val。
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.use.description:
Install the Vue.js plugin. If the plugin is an object, it must expose an install method. If it is a function in itself, it will be regarded as an installation method.
						The installation method will be called with the application instance as the first parameter. The other options parameters passed to use will be passed into the installation method as subsequent parameters.
						When this method is called multiple times on the same plug-in, the plug-in will be installed only once.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.watch.description: The watch API is exactly equivalent to the optional API this.$watch (and the corresponding watch option). Watch needs to listen to a specific data source and have side effects in a separate callback function. By default, it is also lazy-that is, the callback is only called when the listening source changes.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.watchEffect.descripti: Run a function immediately when tracking its dependencies responsively, and re-run it when changing dependencies.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.watchEffect.example:
const count = ref(0)

watchEffect(() => console.log(count.value))
// -> logs 0

setTimeout(() => {
	count.value++
	// -> logs 1
}, 100)
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.withDirectives.descri:
withDirectives can only be used in render or setup functions.
					Allow instructions to be applied to VNode. Return a VNode containing application instructions.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Class<Vue>_.method.withDirectives.exampl:
const app = Vue.createApp({})
app.directive('highlight', {})

import { resolveDirective } from 'vue'
render () {
  const highlightDirective = resolveDirective('highlight')
}
defs/js/vue.3.x.Vue_.property.$attrs.description: Contains feature bindings (except class and style) that are not recognized (and obtained) as props in the parent scope. When a component does not declare any prop, it will include all parent scope bindings (except class and style), and can pass in internal components through v-bind="$attrs"-in the creation of high-level It is very useful when it comes to components.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Vue_.property.$data.description: The data object observed by the Vue instance. The Vue instance delegates access to the properties of its data object.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Vue_.property.$el.description: The root DOM element used by the Vue instance.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Vue_.property.$options.description: Initialization options for the current Vue instance.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Vue_.property.$options.example:
const app = Vue.createApp({
  customOption: 'foo',
  created() {
    console.log(this.$options.customOption) // => 'foo'
  }
})
defs/js/vue.3.x.Vue_.property.$parent.description: The parent instance, if the current instance has one.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Vue_.property.$props.description: The props object received by the current component. The component instance delegates access to the property of its props object.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Vue_.property.$refs.description: An object that holds all DOM elements and component instances that have registered ref characteristics.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Vue_.property.$root.description: The root Vue instance of the current component tree. If the current instance does not have a parent instance, this instance will be itself.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Vue_.property.$slots.description: Used to access the content distributed by the slot. Each named slot has its corresponding attribute (for example: the content in slot="foo" will be found in vm.$slots.foo). The default attribute includes all nodes that are not included in the named slot.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Vue_.property.$slots.example:
const app = Vue.createApp({})

app.component('blog-post', {
  render() {
    return Vue.h('div', [
      Vue.h('header', this.$slots.header()),
      Vue.h('main', this.$slots.default()),
      Vue.h('footer', this.$slots.footer())
   ])
  }
})
defs/js/vue.3.x.Vue_.property.config.description: Contains the object of the application configuration.
defs/js/vue.3.x.Vue_.property.config.example:
import { createApp } from 'vue'
const app = createApp({})

app.config = {...}

defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.activated.des: Called when the keep-alive component is activated.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.activated.rem: This hook is not called during server-side rendering.
After the instance is initialized, the data observer and event/watcher are called before the event configuration.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.beforeDestroy: Called before the instance is destroyed. At this step, the instance is still fully available.
This hook is not called during server-side rendering.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.beforeMount.d: Called before the start of the mount: the relevant render function is called for the first time. This hook is not called during server-side rendering.
Called when the data is updated, before the virtual DOM is patched. This is suitable for accessing the existing DOM before the update, such as manually removing the added event listener.
This hook is not called during server-side rendering, because only the first rendering will be performed on the server-side.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.comments.desc: When set to true, HTML comments in the template will be preserved and rendered. The default behavior is to discard them.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.comments.rema: This option is only available when compiling in the browser in the full build version.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.components.de: Contains a hash table of the components available for the Vue instance.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.computed.desc: The calculated properties will be mixed into the Vue instance. The this context of all getters and setters are automatically bound to Vue instances.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.computed.exam:
var vm = new Vue({
  data: { a: 1 },
  computed: {
      aDouble: function () {
      return this.a * 2
    },
        aPlus: {
      get: function () {
        return this.a + 1
      },
      set: function (v) {
        this.a = v - 1
      }
    }
  }
})
vm.aPlus   // => 2
vm.aPlus = 3
vm.a       // => 2
vm.aDouble // => 4
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.created.descr: It is called immediately after the instance is created. In this step, the instance has completed the following configurations: data observer, calculation of attributes and methods, and watch/event event callbacks. However, the mounting phase has not yet started, and the $el property is currently not visible.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.data.descript: The data object of the Vue instance.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.data.example:
var data = { a: 1 }

var vm = new Vue({
  data: data
})
vm.a // => 1
vm.$data === data // => true

var Component = Vue.extend({
  data: function () {
    return { a: 1 }
  }
})
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.deactivated.d: Called when the keep-alive component is disabled.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.deactivated.r: This hook is not called during server-side rendering.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.delimiters.de: Change the plain text to insert the separator.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.destroyed.des: Called after the Vue instance is destroyed. After the call, everything indicated by the Vue instance will be unbound, all event listeners will be removed, and all child instances will be destroyed.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.destroyed.rem: This hook is not called during server-side rendering.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.directives.de: Contains a hash table of the instructions available for the Vue instance.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.el.descriptio: Provide an existing DOM element on the page as the mount target of the Vue instance. It can be a CSS selector or an HTMLElement instance.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.errorCaptured: 2.5.0+ new is called when an error from descendant components is caught. This hook will receive three parameters: the error object, the component instance where the error occurred, and a string containing the source of the error. This hook can return false to prevent the error from continuing to propagate upward.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.extends.descr: Allows declaration to extend another component (can be a simple option object or constructor) without using Vue.extend. This is mainly to facilitate the expansion of single-file components.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.extends.examp:
var CompA = { ... }

var CompB = {
  extends: CompA,
  ...
}
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.filters.descr: A hash table containing the filters available for the Vue instance.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.functional.de: Make the component stateless (no data) and no instance (no this context). They use a simple render function to return virtual nodes to make them easier to render.
By default, attribute bindings of the parent scope that are not considered props will be 'retreated' and applied as normal HTML attributes to the root element of the child component. When writing a component that wraps a target element or another component, this may not always conform to the expected behavior. By setting inheritAttrs to false, these default behaviors will be removed. These features can be made effective through the instance attribute $attrs (also new in 2.4), and can be explicitly bound to non-root elements through v-bind.
This option does not affect the binding of class and style.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.inject.descri: Need to be used with provide
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.inject.remark: provide and inject mainly provide use cases for high-level plug-in/component libraries. It is not recommended for direct use in application code.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.methods.descr: Methods will be mixed into the Vue instance. These methods can be accessed directly through the VM instance, or used in instruction expressions. This in the method is automatically bound to a Vue instance.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.methods.examp:
var vm = new Vue({
  data: { a: 1 },
  methods: {
    plus: function () {
      this.a++
    }
  }
})
vm.plus()
vm.a // 2
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.methods.remar: Note that arrow functions should not be used to define method functions (eg plus: () => this.a++). The reason is that the arrow function is bound to the context of the parent scope, so this will not point to the Vue instance as expected, and this.a will be undefined.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.mixins.descri:
The mixins option accepts an array of mixed objects. These mixed instance objects can contain options like normal instance objects, and they will finally be merged using the same option merge logic in Vue.extend(). Example: If your mixin contains a hook and the creation component itself also has one, two functions will be called.
Mixin hooks are called in sequence according to the incoming order, and are called before calling the component's own hook.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.mixins.exampl:
var mixin = {
  created: function () { console.log(1) }
}
var vm = new Vue({
  created: function () { console.log(2) },
  mixins: [mixin]
})
// => 1
// => 2
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.model.descrip: Allows a custom component to customize prop and event when using v-model. By default, the v-model on a component will use value as prop and input as event, but some input types such as radio buttons and checkbox buttons may want to use value prop for different purposes. Use the model option to avoid conflicts caused by these situations.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.model.example:
Vue.component('my-checkbox', {
  model: {
    prop: 'checked',
    event: 'change'
  },
  props: {
    // this allows using the `value` prop for a different purpose
    value: String,
    // use `checked` as the prop which take the place of `value`
    checked: {
      type: Number,
      default: 0
    }
  },
  // ...
})
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.mounted.descr: el is replaced by the newly created vm.$el, and the hook is called after it is mounted on the instance. If the root instance mounts an element in the document, vm.$el is also in the document when mounted is called.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.mounted.examp:
Note mounted does not promise that all sub-components are also mounted together. 
If you want to wait until the entire view is rendered, you can replace mounted with vm.$nextTick: 

    mounted: function () {
      this.$nextTick(function () {
        // Code that will run only after the
        // entire view has been rendered
      })
    }
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.mounted.remar: This hook is not called during server-side rendering。
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.name.descript:
Allow component templates to call themselves recursively. Note that when the component is registered globally with Vue.component(), the global ID is automatically used as the component's name. 

Another benefit of specifying the name option is to facilitate debugging. Named components have more friendly warning messages. In addition, when there is vue-devtools, unnamed components will be displayed as <AnonymousComponent>, which has no semantics. By providing the name option, a component tree with more semantic information can be obtained.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.parent.descri: Specify the parent instance of the created instance, and establish a parent-child relationship between the two. The child instance can use this.$parent to access the parent instance, and the child instance is pushed into the $children array of the parent instance.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.parent.remark: Use $parent and $children sparingly-their main purpose is to serve as an emergency method for accessing components. It is more recommended to use props and events to achieve parent-child component communication
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.props.descrip: props can be an array or an object, used to receive data from the parent component. Props can be a simple array, or use an object as a substitute. The object allows configuration of advanced options, such as type detection, custom checksums, and setting default values.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.props.example:
Vue.component('props-demo-simple', {
  props: ['size', 'myMessage']
})

// 对象语法，提供校验
Vue.component('props-demo-advanced', {
  props: {
        height: Number,
       age: {
      type: Number,
      default: 0,
      required: true,
      validator: function (value) {
        return value >= 0
      }
    }
  }
})
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.propsData.des: Pass props when creating an instance. The main function is to facilitate testing.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.propsData.exa:
var Comp = Vue.extend({
  props: ['msg'],
  template: '
{{ msg }}
'
})

var vm = new Comp({
  propsData: {
    msg: 'hello'
  }
})
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.provide.descr: Need to be used with inject
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.provide.remar: provide and inject mainly provide use cases for high-level plug-in/component libraries. It is not recommended for direct use in application code.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.render.descri: The replacement scheme of string templates allows you to take advantage of JavaScript's maximum programming capabilities. The rendering function receives a createElement method as the first parameter to create a VNode.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.render.remark: If the render function in the Vue option exists, the Vue constructor will not compile the rendering function from the HTML template extracted from the template option or the mounted element specified by the el option.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.renderError.d: New in 2.2.0. Only work in a developer environment. When the render function encounters an error, another rendering output is provided. The error will be passed to renderError as the second parameter. This function is very useful in conjunction with hot-reload.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.renderError.e:
new Vue({
  render (h) {
    throw new Error('oops')
  },
  renderError (h, err) {
    return h('pre', { style: { color: 'red' }}, err.stack)
  }
}).$mount('#app')
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.template.desc: A string template is used as the identifier of the Vue instance. The template will replace the mounted element. The content of the mounted element will be ignored, unless the content of the template has a distribution slot.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.template.rema: If a rendering function is included in the Vue options, the template will be ignored.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.updated.descr: The virtual DOM is re-rendered and patched due to data changes, after which the hook will be called.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.updated.remar: This hook is not called during server-side rendering.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.watch.descrip: For an object, the key is the expression to be observed, and the value is the corresponding callback function. The value can also be a method name, or an object containing options. The Vue instance will call $watch() when it is instantiated, traversing every attribute of the watch object.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.watch.example:
var vm = new Vue({
  data: {
    a: 1,
    b: 2,
    c: 3,
    d: 4,
    e: {
      f: {
        g: 5
      }
    }
  },
  watch: {
    a: function (val, oldVal) {
      console.log('new: %s, old: %s', val, oldVal)
    },
       b: 'someMethod',
        c: {
      handler: function (val, oldVal) { /* ... */ },
      deep: true
    },
        d: {
      handler: function (val, oldVal) { /* ... */ },
      immediate: true
    },
    e: [
      function handle1 (val, oldVal) { /* ... */ },
      function handle2 (val, oldVal) { /* ... */ }
    ],
    // watch vm.e.f's value: {g: 5}
    'e.f': function (val, oldVal) { /* ... */ }
  }
})
vm.a = 2 // => new: 2, old: 1
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.ComponentOptions_.property.watch.remarks: Note that arrow functions should not be used to define watcher functions (eg searchQuery: newValue => this.updateAutocomplete(newValue)). The reason is that the arrow function is bound to the context of the parent scope, so this will not point to the Vue instance as expected, and this.updateAutocomplete will be undefined.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.Route_.property.fullPath.description: The parsed URL contains the full path of query parameters and hash.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.Route_.property.hash.description: The hash value (with #) of the current route. If there is no hash value, it is an empty string.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.Route_.property.matched.description: An array containing the routing records of all nested path fragments of the current route.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.Route_.property.name.description: The name of the current route.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.Route_.property.params.description: A key/value object contains dynamic fragments and full-match fragments. If there are no routing parameters, it is an empty object.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.Route_.property.path.description: The path of the current route.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.Route_.property.redirectedFrom.descripti: If there is a redirection, it is the name of the route from which the redirection originated.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.RouterOptions_.property.base.description: The base path of the application.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.RouterOptions_.property.fallback.descrip:
When the browser does not support history.pushState to control whether the routing should fall back to hash mode. The default value is true.
                    
                        In IE9, setting to false will cause each router-link navigation to trigger a full page refresh. It can be used for server-side rendering applications working under IE9, because a hash mode URL does not support server-side rendering.
The default 'active class name' of the global configuration <router-link>.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.RouterOptions_.property.linkExactActiveC: Global configuration <router-link> The default class that is precisely activated.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.RouterOptions_.property.parseQuery.descr: Provide parsing/de-analyzing functions for custom query strings. Override the default behavior.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.VueRouter_.method.back.description: Take a step back in the history record.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.VueRouter_.method.forward.description: Take a step forward in the history record.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.VueRouter_.method.getMatchedComponents.d: Return the target position or the component array matched by the current route (the definition/construction class of the array, not an instance). It is usually used when the data rendered on the server is preloaded.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.VueRouter_.method.go.description: How many steps forward or backward in the history record, similar to window.history.go(n).
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.VueRouter_.method.onError.description: Called when an error occurs during the route navigation.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.VueRouter_.method.onReady.description: Called when the route completes initial navigation.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.VueRouter_.method.push.description: Navigate to the URL, this method will add a new record to the history stack.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.VueRouter_.method.replace.description: Replace the current history record, it will not add a new record to history.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.VueRouter_.property.$route.description: The route information object corresponding to the current route.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.VueRouter_.property.app.description: Vue root instance with router configured.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.VueRouter_.property.currentRoute.descrip: The route information object corresponding to the current route.
defs/js/vuerouter.3.x.VueRouter_.property.mode.description: The mode used by the route.

defs/js/vuex.3.x.Vuex.Store_.method.commit.description: Submit the mutation. There can be root: true in options, which allows the root mutation to be submitted in the namespace module.
defs/js/vuex.3.x.Vuex.Store_.method.dispatch.description: Distribute the action. There can be root: true in options, which allows the root action to be distributed in the namespace module. Return a Promise that resolves all triggered action handlers.
defs/js/vuex.3.x.Vuex.Store_.method.hotUpdate.description: Hot replacement of new actions and mutations.
defs/js/vuex.3.x.Vuex.Store_.method.replaceState.descript: Replace the root state of the store, only use state merging or time travel debugging.
defs/js/vuex.3.x.Vuex.Store_.method.subscribe.description: Subscribe to store mutations. Usually used for plug-ins.
defs/js/vuex.3.x.Vuex.Store_.method.subscribeAction.descr: Subscribe to the store's action. Usually used for plug-ins.
defs/js/vuex.3.x.Vuex.Store_.method.watch.description:
Responsively listen to the return value of fn and call the callback function when the value changes. fn receives the state of the store as the first parameter, and its getter as the second parameter. Finally, it receives an optional object parameter that represents the parameter of Vue's vm.$watch method.

To stop listening, call the function returned by this method to stop listening.
defs/js/vuex.3.x.VuexContext_.property.rootGetters.descri: Equivalent to `store.getters`, only exists in the module
defs/js/vuex.3.x.VuexContext_.property.rootState.descript: Equivalent to `store.state`, only exists in the module
defs/js/vuex.3.x.VuexContext_.property.state.description: Equivalent to `store.state`, If it is in the module, it is a local state
defs/js/vuex.3.x.Class<Vuex>_.method.createNamespacedHelp: Create namespace-based component binding helper functions. It returns an object containing mapState, mapGetters, mapActions, and mapMutations. They are all bound to the given namespace.
defs/js/vuex.3.x.Class<Vuex>_.method.mapActions.descripti: Create component methods to dispatch actions.
defs/js/vuex.3.x.Class<Vuex>_.method.mapGetters.descripti: Create a calculated property for the component to return the return value of the getter.
defs/js/vuex.3.x.Class<Vuex>_.method.mapMutations.descrip: Create the component method to submit the mutation.
defs/js/vuex.3.x.Class<Vuex>_.method.mapState.description: Create a calculated property for the component to return the state in the Vuex store.
defs/js/vuex.3.x.Vuex_Store_Options_.property.actions.des: Register the action on the store. The processing function always accepts context as the first parameter and payload as the second parameter (optional).
defs/js/vuex.3.x.Vuex_Store_Options_.property.getters.des: Register a getter on the store
defs/js/vuex.3.x.Vuex_Store_Options_.property.modules.des: Objects containing submodules will be merged into the store
defs/js/vuex.3.x.Vuex_Store_Options_.property.mutations.d: To register a mutation on the store, the processing function always accepts state as the first parameter (if defined in the module, it is the local state of the module), and payload as the second parameter (optional).
defs/js/vuex.3.x.Vuex_Store_Options_.property.plugins.des: An array containing the plugin methods applied on the store. These plugins directly receive store as the only parameter, and can monitor mutations (used for external data persistence, recording or debugging) or submit mutations (used for internal data, such as websocket or some observers)
defs/js/vuex.3.x.Vuex_Store_Options_.property.state.descr: The root state object of the Vuex store instance.
defs/js/vuex.3.x.Vuex_Store_Options_.property.strict.desc: Put the Vuex store into strict mode. In strict mode, any modification of the Vuex state outside of the mutation processing function will throw an error.
